In a nutshell: nations can agree to cooperate. But no sovereign state fully surrenders itself to an external monopoly of the use of force.
The US has an interest in maintaining freedom of navigation as it is customarily recognized. But there is no controlling legal authority.
But you'll never hear me hang my hat on it being "illegal". I will say US has interest in freedom of navigation under intl law (i.e. custom)
China's claim to South China Sea may or may not be unjust, aggressive, violate treaties, limpinge on other nations' legit interests ...
When Russia invaded Crimea, it wasn't illegal. Arguably it was unjust, aggressive, violated treaties or UN charter. But no legal authority.
But when critics speak of "illegal" wars they don't usually have this level of precision in mind. They just mean they object to it.
Of course, it may be true that waging a war is "illegal" under domestic law, i.e., not under the proper authority of the state.
I know, "international law", "the law of nations". But "law" in this sense really is a loose term what is properly understood as custom.
Yes, treaties may exist, but treaties are better understood as agreements made out of share interests, not "legally" binding. By what law?
An accepted legal authority is precisely what does NOT exist in disputes between sovereign states.
Phrase "illegal war" is nonsense. Just/unjust, aggressive/defensive, all legit distinctions. "Illegal" presupposes accepted legal authority.
